out 1215":"okolo 1215","about 1247":"okolo 1247","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1215–about 1247":"omkring 1215–omkring 1247","1245–Female":"1245–Afdød","1215–1247":"1215–1247","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"omkring 1215","about 1247":"omkring 1247","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England"},"nl":{"about 1215–about 1247":"circa 1215–circa 1247","1245–Female":"1245–Overleden","1215–1247":"1215–1247","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"circa 1215","about 1247":"circa 1247","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England"},"en":{"about 1215–about 1247":"about 1215–about 1247","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","1215–1247":"1215–1247","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"about 1215","about 1247":"about 1247","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fitzwallter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English, Irish: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , ‘son of  <i>Walter</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitzwater","meanings":["Irish: altered form of <b>Fitzwalter</b>, a patronymic from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , meaning ‘son of <i>Walter</i>’.","History: This is the name of a family of Norman origin, descended from Godfrey, Count of Brionne (died <i>c.</i> 1010). Godfrey's grandson, Richard FitzGilbert, accompanied William the Conqueror and was made Lord of Clare. His great-grandson was Robert FitzWalter, one of the barons who guaranteed the Magna Carta in 1215."]},{"name":"Walter","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Matthew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathew","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":9,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Matthew Fitzwallter was born about 1215, in Leicestershire, England. He had at least 1 daughter. He died about 1247, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1215–about 1247":"umbes 1215–umbes 1247","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1215–1247":"1215–1247","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"umbes 1215","about 1247":"umbes 1247","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1215–about 1247":"noin 1215–noin 1247","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1215–1247":"1215–1247","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"noin 1215","about 1247":"noin 1247","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England"},"fr":{"about 1215–about 1247":"environ 1215–environ 1247","1245–Female":"1245–Décédée","1215–1247":"1215–1247","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"environ 1215","about 1247":"environ 1247","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Matthew Fitzwallter est né environ 1215, à Leicestershire, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé environ 1247, à l’âge de 34 ans."},"de":{"about 1215–about 1247":"um 1215–um 1247"